{{DISPLAYTITLE:mBillionth Award South Asia}} The '''mBillionth Award South Asia''' is presented each year since 2010<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/ksrtcs-mobile-service-gets-award/article537466.ece "KSRTC's mobile service gets award"], [[The Hindu]], 28 July 2010</ref> for socially valuable innovations in [[mobile communications]] in [[South Asia]]. The scheme is run by the Digital Empowerment Foundation,<ref>{{cite news|title=mBillionth Award 2012: An Ecosystem for Mobilepreneurs|url=https://telecomtalk.info/mbillionth-award-2012-ecosystem-mobilepreneurs/92270/|work=Telecom Talk|date=20 April 2012}}</ref> an Indian [[NGO]] seeking to improve access to and usage of digital communications.<ref>{{cite web|title=Digital Empowerment Foundation (DEF)|url=http://www.eldis.org/go/home&id=73039&type=Organisation#.WJC-EGdBqk1|website=Eldis|publisher=Institute of Development Studies|accessdate=31 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=pickme>[https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-4141976381.html "Pickme Wins Mbillionth Award 2016."] The Daily Mirror (Colombo, Sri Lanka). HT Media Ltd. 10 August 2016. Retrieved January 31, 2017 from HighBeam Research</ref>
==Aims== The stated mission of the mBillionth Awards is "to recognise and honor excellence in mobile communications across South Asia... recognising and felicitating mobile innovations, applications and content services delivery."<ref name=fishers>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/MSSRF-app-for-fishermen-wins-award/articleshow/38766945.cms "MSSRF app for fishermen wins award"], [[Times of India]], 21 July 2014</ref> Founded in 2010, the awards are directed towards those innovations in mobile communications that make for widespread adoption of the technology, promising empowerment and social gain.<ref name=mint2010>[https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2094918451.html "Rewarding the best mobile innovations."] Mint. 26 July 2010. Retrieved January 31, 2017 from HighBeam Research</ref> The scheme seeks further to facilitate networking among inventors and developers in this field.<ref name=bcouncil />
==Eligibility== The award is open to governments, individuals, private sector companies, academic institutions, and NGOs in any of the eight [[SAARC]] countries: Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. Entry is by self-nomination.
==Selection process== Nominations for the award are pre-filtered and the final selection is carried out by a Grand Jury. In 2016 the number of nominations received was 348;<ref name=SLIIT /> of these 60 were considered by the Grand Jury of 15 members, who selected 25 winners and 6 Special Mentions.
